:YeastPathways_YEAST-4AMINOBUTMETAB-PWY
        a                   obo:GO_0006540 , owl:NamedIndividual ;
        rdfs:comment        "The non-protein amino acid gamma-aminobutyrate (GABA) plays an important role in mammalian neurotransmission, plant development, and in S.cerevisiae, nitrogen utilization and oxidative stress tolerance |CITS: [11031268]|, |CITS:[3888627]|. In yeast, GABA accumulation occurs either through permease-mediated uptake by Uga4p, Put4p, and Gap1p, or it is produced intracellularly via glutamate degradation by the glutamate decarboxylase Gad1p |CITS: [11031268]|, |CITS: [3888627]|. The presence of GABA causes an increase in expression of the genes UGA1 and UGA2, which encode the enzymes responsible for degrading GABA into succinate |CITS:[3888627]|. This GABA-induced upregulation is mediated by the transcriptional activators Uga3p and Uga35p/Dal81p |CITS:[2653828]|. These transcription factors bind to upstream activation sites in the promoters of GABA-regulated genes known as the UAS-GABA |CITS:[12235130]|, |CITS: [2653828]|. Levels of UGA2 transcript are also upregulated under conditions of oxidative stress |CITS:[11031268]|. S.cerevisiae cells in which GABA degradation is blocked are more sensitive to oxidative stress and can no longer grow on GABA as their sole nitrogen source |CITS:[11031268]|, |CITS:[3888627]|." ;
        rdfs:label          "4-aminobutyrate degradation" ;
        dc:contributor      "https://orcid.org/0000-0001-9799-5523" , "GOC:sgd_curators" ;
        dc:date             "2026-04-22" ;
        pav:providedBy      "http://www.yeastgenome.org" ;
        oboInOwl:hasDbXref  "YeastPathways_YEAST-4AMINOBUTMETAB-PWY" ;
        skos:note           "org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.Pathway" .

